HTTP -> HTTPS in README.md
HTTP -> HTTPS
Merge support for multiple nightlies per day. Close #24.

Combine the 2 bounding-buildids tests, since `testing` makes both assertions run, even if the first fails.

Rename things to "test-whatever", because Clojure gets grumpy when I shadow things I've imported. This is the spelling convention they use in Leiningen itself. I find it redundant, but I don't have a better idea atm.
Don't use the redundant "..." spelling when there's only one build.

Understand that there may be multiple nightly builds in a day. Fix #19.

Find the earliest and latest builds in the requested day, and include the pushlog that spans them all in the alert mail.

Also replace `get` with callable vectors, which will raise an exception early if the linked text isn't what we expected, rather than puttering onward with a nil.
Compile medusa.js for recent changes

Put a note in the alert email that the changeset URL may be for the wrong Nightly

Issue #19

Stop emailing rvitillo for alerts.

It turns out that rvitillo was added to every email alert through a
subscription to the entire Histogram Regression detector.

No one else used that system, so just remove it from the email list.

Fixes mozilla/cerberus#29
Include release deployment instructions in the README.

Change over to MPLv2

Nothing particularly wrong with the EclipsePL, but it's more on-brand to be MPL :)
Merge first naive test. Close #23.

Add a smoke test for find-date-buildid.

This should help us revise it to return multiple buildids without having to test in production.

Remove non-working example core_test.clj, which crashed because it required "medusa.core" rather than "clj.medusa.core".
Remove unused and duplicate requires.

Take a hatchet to Persona.

Roughly remove Persona, login, logout, and subscription support from Medusa.

This probably isn't removing everything it can, and may remove more than it
should.

Merge pull request #6 from Uberi/fix-date-picker

Fix the datepicker choosing the next day

Work around bug in bootstrap-datepicker in which dates are selected in UTC and then have the timezone offset added before being passed to callbacks.

Now we simply subtract the timezone offset to get the exact date in UTC.
